<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel checks on value added tax administration between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The present material informs about the progress and results of parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvy higher control office of the Slovak Republic, which focused on the area of value added tax administration and the use of the Value Added Tax Information Exchange System (VIES).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so the revenue from value added tax affects not only the state budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel control actions were aimed in particular at checking the procedure of tax authorities in examining the amount of value added tax paid in commercial transactions carried out between member states of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of the VIES system has enabled the electronic exchange of information on the registration of value added tax payers in each Member State of the European Union and on commercial transactions made by such payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">The discrepancy between the data in the VIES system and the data in the value added tax return filed by the payer should alert the tax administrator to suspicious cases and allow the detection of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefit of the parallel checks carried out consisted not only in the exchange of information on the procedure of financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but in particular in the examination of the use of VIES in the control of the application of the right to value added tax exemption in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The lessons learned from the implementation of parallel controls are beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of further parallel controls in cooperation with the control institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel checks on value added tax administration for the period from 1 January 2007 to 31 December 2006 5. 2004 to 30. 6. 2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Inspection number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of control: (GB) Value added tax administration, (SK) Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and the fulfilment of tasks within the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO, the Czech Republic) and the Najvyšší control office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "SAO SR") concluded on 12 December 2004 that the Slovak Republic's audit office, the Czech Republic, was established in Slovakia. 9. 2005 Cooperation Agreement in control activities.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in the parallel control actions carried out "Value Added Tax Administration", included in the plan of control activities of the SAO, Cr for 2005 under No. 05/19 and "Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the management, control and enforcement of dane from the added value and the fulfilment of the tasks under the VIES system for the exchange of information medácií medzi by the member landscapes of the ECA", included in the plan of control activities of the SAO SR under No. 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">The control actions carried out in parallel were coordinated checks.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated control has been processed within the meaning of European Enforcement Regulation No 31 for INTOSAI control standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information to the extent set out in the contract and drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated control was to verify selected cases of delivery and acquisition of goods in suspicious commercial transactions between value added tax payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "Cr") and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "Slovakia").</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties have contractually committed themselves to providing information from public sources, from the Value Added Tax Information Exchange System (VIES) and data on received and submitted requests for verification of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the Czech Republic, the control was carried out by the Department of State Budget and the Territorial Departments of Central Bohemia, North-West Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited persons were the Ministry of Finance and 12 tax offices: the Tax Office in Mladá Boleslav, the Tax Office in Kolín, the Financial Office in Teplice, the Tax Office in Karlovy Vary, the Tax Office in Tábor, the Tax Office brno III, the Tax Office in Znojmo, the Tax Office in Zlín, the Tax Office in Šumperk, the Financial Office ostrava I, the Tax Office for Prague 7 and the Tax Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">Control in the territory of the Slovak Republic was carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with the Expos of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 9 selected tax offices: Tax Office Bratislava I, Tax Office Komárno, Tax Office Trenčín, Tax Office Prievidza, Daňový úrad Zvolen, Daňový úrad Dolný Kubín, Tax Office Košice II, Tax Úradice V and Tax Council Michal.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of checks:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel control actions was to examine the procedure of financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") after the integration of the Czech Republic and the Czech Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as "the EU") and to examine the use of the VIES electronic information system, in particular when checking the application of the vat exemption entitlement.</seg>
<seg id="27">The period of control in the coordinated period was from 1 January 2005 to 31 December 2005. 5. 2004 to 30. 6. 2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of the results and evaluation of parallel control actions An electronic VIES system is in place in EU Member States, which allows tax authorities to check whether the supplier has been entitled to exempt taxable transactions from VAT and, in the country of destination, to check whether the purchaser has properly admitted and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="29">VIES is not centralised within the EU, each Member State develops its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The inspection identified differences of national systems of VIES in the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">The summary reports shall indicate the values of the delivery of goods to other EU Member States, the values of the services provided shall not be included in the recapitulative reports.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from summary reports submitted by Czech payers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of the tax authorities, where they are compared with data on supplies of goods to other EU Member States mentioned in vat tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The tax authorities transmit the summary report data to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends it to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In Slovakia, the data from the summary reports submitted by Slovak payers at the tax offices are only transferred to electronic form and processed centrally at the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Society (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers report the value of the supply of goods and the value of the supply of services to other EU Member States on separate lines of VAT returns, which makes it possible to compare the values specified in the summary reports with the values of the delivery of goods according to vat returns and to identify their possible differences.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the Czech Technical Party, the values of the goods and services supplied to other EU Member States are reported cumulatively on the common line of the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, in the SR, the system does not automatically identify differences between the values of delivery of goods according to VAT returns and summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="38">The separate reporting of the values of supplies of goods in VAT returns makes it possible to use the results of comparison of data when checking the exemption of supplies of goods to the EU from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="39">The data received from summary reports submitted by payers in other EU Member States are processed at CLO and compared with the value of the acquisition of goods given by the payer from the Czech Republic or Slovakia in vat returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the SR, this data is sent to the tax authorities and the tax authorities decide for themselves which cases of differences will be examined.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) determines which quantified differences between the values of delivery and acquisition of goods must be examined by the tax authorities and will transmit to the local tax authorities a list of these cases.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that the most significant derogations will ensure that VAT was granted at the correct amount when the goods were acquired.</seg>
<seg id="43">Furthermore, the check highlighted some problems in the VAT management system of complications caused by the different reporting of intra-Community transactions (i.e. the supply and acquisition of goods carried out by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Summaries are submitted in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum deadline for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">Shortening the period for which summaries are submitted to one month, together with the reduction of the processing period, would allow earlier access to data in VIES.</seg>
<seg id="46">Thus, tax authorities could more effectively verify whether VAT has been granted at the correct level in intra-Community acquisitions.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, the submission of VAT returns and summaries for the same tax year (month) would allow for a faster verification of whether the payer has reported the same value of supplies of goods to the EU in both the recapitulative statement and the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="48">The differences between the values of delivery of goods reported by EU payers and the values of the acquisition of goods reported by the payers from the Czech Republic or The Czech Republic were due, inter alia, to the value of the goods reported by the payers from the Czech Republic. different reporting of intra-Community delivery and acquisition data in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="49">This included, for example, the placing of advances received in summary reports, or the reporting of intra-community deliveries in the vendor's recapitulative statement in a quarter other than intra-Community acquisitions in the purchaser's VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="50">Unifying the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would lead to a streamlining of the control activities of national tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was also focused on the examination of selected intra-Community transactions carried out between the two states.</seg>
<seg id="52">Together, a total of 40 cases of commercial transactions carried out between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined, for which there were doubts about their implementation or suspected vat evasion.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR found, inter alia, the following:</seg>
<seg id="54">tax entities have reported in their VAT returns for the purpose of unlawfully obtaining an excessive VAT deduction, the execution of intra-Community transactions that have not actually taken place;</seg>
<seg id="55">tax entities have reported intra-community supplies in carousel transactions in which there has been a deliberate multiple reduction in the value of supplies in order to draw excessive VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">suppliers reported in their VAT tax returns and summaries intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to purchasers who were so-called VAT-exempt. 'lost companies' and have not admitted the tax on the goods acquired;</seg>
<seg id="57">suppliers have made intra-Community supplies of VAT-exempt goods to tax entities that have not been registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In such cases, the supply should not have been exempted from VAT and should have been subject to vat in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">suppliers reported intra-Community supplies of higher value in their VAT returns than those reported by intra-Community acquisitions, in some cases the VAT was awarded at an incorrect amount.</seg>
<seg id="60">The findings of the control action showed that VIES provides tax authorities with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">Tax authorities should pay particular attention to the thorough examination of the differences between data reported by VAT payers and data in the VIES system and the use of all information in tax proceedings.</seg>
