<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">On the basis of international cooperation, compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT and the use of VIES for the exchange of information between EU Member States has been examined, in particular when monitoring the application of the right to VAT exemptions.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation made it possible to examine selected intra-community transactions carried out between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="371">By examining the transactions selected, it was found that, on the basis of the international exchange of information, the tax authorities of both countries revealed the cases of companies carrying out fictitious intra-Community business transactions in order to obtain excessive VAT deductions, as well as cases where the purchasers did not admit VAT on the received supplies of goods at the correct amount.</seg>
<seg id="372">Furthermore, the control identified differences in the processing and use of VIES data by the tax administrations of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The review also highlighted problems caused by the different reporting of data on intra-Community supplies and purchases of goods in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="374">Unifying the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would lead to a streamlining of the control activities of national tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="375">By examining the procedure of the financial or tax authorities in the management of VAT and the use of the VIES system, it was found that the tax or tax authorities did not make sufficient use of all the possibilities of the VIES system and the relevant legal authorisations.</seg>
<seg id="376">Furthermore, it was found that VIES did not provide up-to-date information on the supply of goods and on the validity of the registration of tax entities for VAT in all cases.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SA SAO compared the data on the occurrence of erroneous data in the SH, processed before the start of the inspection, with the data processed after the completion of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="378">It was clear from the comparison of these data that the inspection of the SAO SR had an impact not only on the reduction of the number of SH with the erroneously mentioned VAT number, but also on the reduction of the number of unrecedified errors in the SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In the event of irregularities in the reported data, the SAO SR asked the tax authorities to carry out local investigations or to carry out tax checks.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, the Czech Republic did not have such an option within the framework of the current legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The findings of the control action showed that VIES provided tax authorities with the basic information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">Given that there is still room for tax evasion in this area, there is a need to pay increased attention to intra-Community transactions in the management of VAT.</seg>
