<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of value added tax administration and excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material provides an overview of the progress and results of parallel control actions carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Najvy higher control office of the Slovak Republic, which focused on the area of value added management and excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the supreme control offices of the two countries was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement in control activities concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The theme of parallel control actions has been chosen in view of the fact that indirect taxes contribute significantly to the revenues of the state budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The design of value added tax, allowing the repayment of the excessive deduction, provides scope for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High rates of excise duty, in particular for tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean a high profit for those who escape taxation by illegally selling such goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Given the need to address this issue comprehensively throughout the European Union, the highest audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union have created a working group of VAT Working Group, involving the most active control bodies of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest contribution of the control actions carried out can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but in particular in a joint effort to identify problematic areas of indirect tax administration in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The experience gained and the knowledge will be used in the framework of planned indirect tax controls, aimed primarily at involving tax authorities of both States in the VIES system, allowing for control of the movement of goods between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the control of value added tax and excise duties for the period 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Inspection number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duty</seg>
<seg id="17">(S)(100)( Control of the tax administrator's procedure for the administration, control and recovery of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="18">On 11.2. In 2004, the Cooperation Agreement was concluded in the control activities between the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the Najvy higher control office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO SR). The subject of the contract was cooperation in the parallel control actions carried out 'Value added tax and excise duty', included in the SAO's control activity plan for 2004 under No 04/07 and "Control of the procedure of the dane administrator in the management, control and enforcement of the tax on the added value and the consumption taxes", included in the audit activity plan of the SAO SR under No. 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information to the extent set out in the contract and drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">In the contract, the two parties undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the customs administration database and from the files of tax authorities kept by tax authorities in the Czech Republic and by tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the Contracting Parties could not obtain when checking the application of value added tax and excise duties on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the respective State.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic"), the control was carried out by the Department of the State Budget and the Territorial Departments of South Bohemia, North-East Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited persons were the Directorate-General of Customs and 12 selected tax offices: The Tax Office for Prague 1, the Tax Office for Prague 3, the Tax Office in České Budějovice, the Tax Office in Frýdek-Místek, the Tax Office in Hodonin, the Tax Office in Jihlava, the Tax Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, the Tax Office in Kroměříž, the Tax Office in Písek, the Tax Office in Rožnov pod Radhoštěm, the Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí , The Tax Office in Velké Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The inspection on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Slovak Republic) was carried out by the Section of the Tax and Customs Administration of the Sao SR in cooperation with the Expos of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Tax office Bratislava pre selected tax entities, Tax Office Bratislava III, Tax Office Trnava, Tax Office Of Pooh-Breeding, Tax Office Banská Bystrica I, Tax Office Liptovský Mikuláš, Tax Office Žilina I, Tax Office Žilina II, Tax Office Košice I and Tax Office Košice IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of the scan</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the control actions was to examine the fulfilment of the obligations of the financial and tax authorities and customs offices in the administration of value added tax and excise duties, with a focus on the collection of these taxes on the import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of the international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic in the Customs Database of the Czech Republic and the Customs Database of the Czech Republic and their subsequent verification in tax returns at the relevant financial or tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recapitulation of the results of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">In the framework of international cooperation, the SAO forwarded 22,206 items of single customs declarations (hereinafter referred to as "JCD") on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and the Czech Republic from the Czech Customs Database and, conversely, the SAO forwarded the SAO from the SR customs database 30 221 jcd items.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison of typed JCD items from the Customs Database of the Czech Republic and the Customs Database of the Czech Republic was carried out.</seg>
<seg id="34">Of the 5,883 selected JCD items from the Czech customs database, a total of 43% of related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Of the 12,343 JCD items selected from the SR customs database, a total of 26% of related JCD entries were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="36">On the basis of unassigned JCD items, a selection of files of tax entities for which the reported imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was carried out at the financial or tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="37">On the basis of the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and the financial and tax authorities, the implementation of the reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified in the territory of the other state.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO SR carried out a joint pilot check at the border customs crossing Stary Hrozenkov - Drietoma, in which the two parties cooperated closely in verifying the correctness of the data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="39">The check did not identify weaknesses in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods carried out in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation made it possible to examine trade transactions between trading partners from both Countries and highlighted shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of the results of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="42">In the field of international cooperation, the control of the SAO and the SAO SR focused on imports and exports of spirits and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, and other types of goods, where appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="43">On the basis of the inspection of the files of tax entities at the selected financial or tax offices, the SAO requested verification of the implementation of exports of goods reported to 40 JCD in the total statistical value of CZK 15,301,093 and the SR SAO on export verification at a statistical value of SK 56,989.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and the SAO found, inter alia, the following:</seg>
<seg id="45">- commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the Customs Database of the Czech Republic and the Customs Database of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="46">- the error rate in entering data into customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports or exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- some exports from the Czech Republic have not been shown to be corresponding imports into the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="48">In such cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of undue application of value added tax deductions,</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax entities have not complied with certain statutory obligations when reporting imports and exports in value added tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="50">- deficiencies have been identified in the activities of the tax authorities and the tax authorities in the management of value added tax and excise duties and in their cooperation with the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the field of value added tax and excise duties, international trade will continue to need to be addressed in order to effectively minimise tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the activities of tax administrations in the exercise of value added tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="53">Effective control of excise duties is the control of the circulation of documents, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information on the import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the status of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="55">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (hereinafter referred to as 'VAT') was levied by the tax authorities or tax authorities on taxable transactions carried out in the country and by customs authorities on importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">The tax revenues were determined by the difference between the selected own tax liability and the refunded excessive VAT deductions at the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenues at customs offices were determined by the amount of taxes collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">The tax collected by the customs authorities was reflected in the deductions of the tax applied to the tax authorities or tax authorities in accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most tax authorities or tax authorities, excessive VAT deductions outweighed the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the main taxes in terms of state budget revenue, as it accounted for about 31% of the tax revenues of the State Budget of the Czech Republic in 2003 and about 42% in tax revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="62">In 2003, the total collection of VAT in the Czech Republic amounted to EUR 162.9 billion. Czk.</seg>
<seg id="63">In 2003, the tax and customs authorities collected a total of EUR 394.3 billion for VAT. Total vat deductions amounted to CZK 231.4 billion. Czk.</seg>
<seg id="64">The total collection of VAT in the SR amounted to EUR 83.8 billion in 2003. Group.</seg>
<seg id="65">In 2003, the tax and customs authorities collected EUR 187.0 billion for VAT. The total of EUR 103.2 billion was eur 103.2 billion and the excess VAT deductions were refunded. Group.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise duties</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties ('spd') was carried out by the competent tax authorities and on imports of products subject to spd by customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The Share of the SpD in tax revenues of the state budget in the Czech Republic in 2003 was approximately 16% and in the Czech Republic about 19%.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of spd collected in the Czech Republic by the tax and customs authorities in 2003 amounted to EUR 85.6 billion. in the Czech Air And amounted to CZK 38.0 billion. Group.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. Course of control action</seg>
<seg id="71">Cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, a comparison was made of imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic, in the second stage the results of this comparison were used in the mutual verification of the realization of selected commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic and in the checks carried out on the territory of both states.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of the control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel CONTROLS of VAT and spd was presented at a working meeting of representatives of the SAO and the SAO SR in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">In November 2003, a coordination meeting was held, at which, inter alia, the Commission adopted a meeting on the coordination of the European Union's foreign and private ly in the european union. agreed the selection of commodities - the types of goods that posed a significant risk in compliance with customs and tax regulations: - alcohol and spirits, tariff headings No. 2207 and 2208, - Tobacco and tobacco products, tariff headings Nos. 2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, subheadings No 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile phones and their accessories, customs tariff subheadings No 8525 20 91 , 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">Both parties agreed that the selection of tax entities for inspection will be made: a) from unassigned items identified by comparison of exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and The Slovak Republic, b) from entities carrying out imports and exports on a regular or one-off basis in large volumes, c) on the basis of findings from the checks carried out by the selected tax and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of customs databases of the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002 tested the mechanism for the mutual assignment of JCD items registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, part of exports from the Czech Republic were compared with imports into the Czech Republic for 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the Customs Tariff:</seg>
