<seg id="128">4.4. Selected control findings for verification of business transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">In the framework of international cooperation, the implementation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified from the documents of customs administrations and financial or tax offices in the territory of the other state.</seg>
<seg id="130">For selected tax entities, the following have been verified:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="132">- fulfilment of the legal conditions for the application of the VAT deduction on imports, the refund of the excess VAT deduction and the application of the VAT exemption on export.</seg>
<seg id="133">The verification of commercial transactions revealed:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. The SAO SR requested verification of the implementation of the export of alcohol at a statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified in the customs database of the Czech Republic corresponding imports in the statistical value of CZK 42,624.r</seg>
<seg id="136">2. The company dealing with the import and export of photographic equipment and accessories applied an excessive VAT deduction of CZK 3,740,664 in the VAT return for December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to check the reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO collected 3 JCD (16 items) in the statistical value of CZK 1,274,822.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SA identified 3 corresponding import JCD (17 items) in the statistical value of 1 724 321 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="139">VAT was paid in the Czech Customs Office in the Czech Customs.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. In 2002, the company whose business was, in particular, the trade in optical devices, applied a total excess deduction of VAT of CZK 4 1 36 000 higher than the tax liability in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="141">To verify the reported business activity, the SAO selected an export JCD (32 items) with a statistical value of CZK 7,154,124.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SA Found that this JCD corresponds to an import JCD (12 items) with a statistical value of 9,653,827 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="143">VAT was paid in the Czech Customs Office in the Czech Customs.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. A company engaged in, inter alia, the purchase of goods for resale and sale, did not show any exports of goods in the VAT vat returns filed in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the Czech Customs Database, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 totalled CZK 3,439,888.</seg>
<seg id="146">On the basis of these facts, the SAO selected a total statistical value of CZK 669,839 to verify 5 export JCDs (5 items).</seg>
<seg id="147">The SAO SR identified 5 corresponding import JCDs (5 items) in the statistical value of 1 012 656 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="148">The inspection of the SAO of the SR at the competent tax office demonstrated the implementation of the declared imports and the payment of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. A company whose business was, inter alia, a company with a business, the purchase of goods for the purpose of its resale and sale, production, installation and repair of electrical machinery and equipment, in 2002 in vat declarations reported exports of goods worth CZK 12,966,706.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the Czech Customs Database, in 2002 the total value of exports was CZK 14,474,381.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export JCDs (59 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,975,122.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO SR identified 13 JCD (50 items) in the SR customs database in a statistical value of 3,621,370 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the customs database of the SR, the corresponding import JCD to 4 export JCDs (9 items) was not identified in the total statistical value of CZK 399,776.</seg>
<seg id="154">The competent tax authority in the SR verified these imports with the tax entity.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity referred to on the JCD as an importer to the SR stated in the register of the local investigation that the imports declared on the Czech export JCDs did not materialise.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO SR therefore asked the local competent tax authority to carry out a tax audit of VAT and corporate tax for the 2002 and 2003 tax years.</seg>
<seg id="157">6. According to the Czech Customs Database, the company engaged in the import and sale of cigarettes exported tobacco stickers in 2002 with a statistical value of CZK 7,338,199 and in 2003 a statistical value of CZK 12,228,545.</seg>
<seg id="158">In 2002 and 2003, the company reported no exports in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) for verification of a total statistical value of CZK 2,471,598.</seg>
<seg id="160">As of the 4 export JCD (4 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,246,860, the SAO SR identified 7 JCD (7 items) in the SR customs database in a statistical value of 2,919,514 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="161">The export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 224,738 was not assigned to the corresponding imports in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="162">7. The software company did not report exports of goods in vat returns for the years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the Czech Customs Database, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 and 2003 totalled CZK 1,630,198.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected 9 JCD (9 items) for verification in the SR for a total statistical value of CZK 755,588.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the customs database of the SR, the SAO SR identified 8 JCD (8 items) in the statistical value of 915 601 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="166">The export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 68,286 was not assigned to the corresponding imports in the customs database of the SR.</seg>
<seg id="167">In these cases, it was not possible to identify in the customs database of the SR corresponding imports to 6 JCD in the statistical value of CZK 692,800.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- to 2 export JCD from the Customs Database of the Czech Republic with a statistical value of CZK 293,024, the corresponding import JCD was not identified in the SR customs database (see paragraphs 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error rate in the entry of data into the customs database, it was not possible to identify certain registered imports, e.g. in the case of imports. in cases where the importer's name was missing or there was an error in the tax identification number (hereinafter referred to as the 'VAT registration number').</seg>
<seg id="171">It is therefore not possible to conclude with certainty that these exports have not materialised.</seg>
<seg id="172">- the 4 export JCDs from the Customs Database of the Czech Republic have not been shown to be imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to the Czech Republic at a statistical value of CZK 399,776 (see point 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In such cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of the dummy export of goods for the purpose of unduly applying the VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services within the control of selected financial or tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of tax entities in the import and export of goods and services and to evaluate the level of cooperation between the financial and customs authorities, the files of tax entities inspected by the tax authorities have been selected according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. tax entities were selected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic: a) with the highest volume of imports, b) with the highest amount of VAT assessed, c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">2. tax entities have been selected from the register of financial or tax authorities according to the above: a) the vat deductions applied on import, b) the excessive VAT deductions applied, c) the right to repayment of the SpD, d) the vat exemption applied on export,</seg>
<seg id="179">3. tax entities for which tax control has been carried out.</seg>
<seg id="180">Sampling was carried out regardless of the country of destination with a focus on risky commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Control findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic for risky commodities in 2002 and 2003 is given in the following table:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Checking the selected sample at tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="184">The SAO focused in particular on the audited tax offices on:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the procedure for the tax authorities to verify the correctness of the VAT declared,</seg>
<seg id="186">- cooperation between the tax authorities and the customs administration,</seg>
<seg id="187">- comparison of data from the customs database with the JCD database at the tax offices, focusing on the comparison of the declared value, the application of the correct rate of VAT following the customs classification of goods or services, or comparison of jcd data and attached invoices with data in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="188">- a comparison of data from VAT returns on transactions carried out and received from abroad with data in the JCD database at tax offices or in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="189">- the method of verifying the right to VAT exemption on the export of goods or services abroad,</seg>
<seg id="190">- a comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services provided declared in VAT returns with data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The JCD database at the tax authorities contained only records of those imports and exports which were obliged to include imports or exports to the tax return.</seg>
<seg id="192">The audited tax authorities examined the files of tax entities which reported imports totalling CZK 60 396 379 in VAT returns in 2002 and 2003. czk 12,644,052 thousand and the corresponding VAT totalling CZK 12,644,052, Czk.</seg>
<seg id="193">Furthermore, the files of tax entities reporting in tax returns for the years 2002 and 2003 were checked with exports totalling CZK 47 323,111 000. Czk.</seg>
<seg id="194">According to the Czech Customs Database, tax entities for which imports and exports between the Czech Republic and The Czech Republic were examined made imports to the Czech Republic from the Czech Republic with a total VAT base of CZK of CZK of CZK 3,759,352,000. CZK 767,607 thousand CZK, VAT czk and exports from the Czech Republic to the Czech Republic with a total statistical value of CZK 1,989,090 thousand. Czk.</seg>
<seg id="195">The differences found between the records in the JCD database at the tax offices and in the Customs Database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- jcd items, which were missing from the customs database of the Czech Republic, were requested directly from the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="197">- for JCD items that were missing from the tax authorities database, it has been verified that the documents are not cancelled,</seg>
<seg id="198">- for JCD items for which different values have been found between the Customs Database of the Czech Republic and the database of tax authorities, the relevant JCD was requested in writing, including attached invoices, at the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="199">The examination found that the JCD database at the tax authorities did not contain, for example, records of import JCDs with a total VAT value of CZK 3 622 000. czk and records of export JCDs with a total statistical value of CZK 9,359 thousand. Czk.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Differences found</seg>
<seg id="201">By comparing the JCD database at tax offices and the accumulated tax liability for 2002 and 2003 in the VAT returns for the selected sample of tax entities, the following differences were found:</seg>
<seg id="202">Differences in values were mainly caused by:</seg>
<seg id="203">- The time shift between the implementation of imports and the exercise of the right to deduct VAT measured on imports of goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The tax entity was able to claim the deduction of the tax on the importation of goods within 3 years of the end of the tax year in which the goods were placed under the procedure in question or, in the case of the temporary importation procedure, no later than 3 years after the end of the tax year in which the scheme was terminated.</seg>
<seg id="205">- The time shift between the implementation of the export and the moment when the tax entity received the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The tax entity was obliged to provide data on the export carried out exempt from the obligation to apply the output tax to the VAT return first for the tax year in which the goods exited the country, if it also had a tax document, which was the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- Failure to fulfil the obligations of tax entities in the reporting of imports and exports in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, tax entities did not include the correct import and export information in their VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">Since the tax entities did not have to attach JCD lists to the VAT declarations filed, it was difficult to check the right to deduct VAT or the exemption from VAT by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2. Synergies between financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">During the period audited, import or export duties and VAT were refunded or remission by the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="212">Tax entities were obliged by law to reduce the previously claimed right to deduct VAT by the amount of tax returned by the customs office in the tax return for the period in which the tax was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legislation provided for the sending of information on changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT from customs offices to the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some audited tax authorities received this information, but irregularly or with considerable time delays and only from certain customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited tax authority did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information on changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the data necessary to check the fulfilment of the legal obligation of the tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002, the customs authorities returned VAT in an amount of more than EUR 319 million. in 2003 in the amount of over CZK 398 million. Czk.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the audit pointed to persistent shortcomings in the activities of tax authorities, some systemic errors in the cooperation of the tax authorities with customs authorities and the non-fulfilment of certain obligations of payers submitting VAT returns and spd.</seg>
<seg id="219">In the management of VAT and the SpD, weaknesses were identified in particular in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="220">(a) when vat registrations are revoked, compliance with the obligation of the payers to pay VAT on the business assets registered or which was to be registered on the date of the deregistration of the registration with which the payer applied the deduction was verified only occasionally,</seg>
<seg id="221">(b) the tax authorities have consistently failed to make use of the possibility of carrying out tax checks or local investigations.</seg>
<seg id="222">This in some cases resulted in insufficient verification of the eligibility of the right to deduct VAT,</seg>
<seg id="223">c) the official records and oral hearing logs did not contain all the necessary data to demonstrate the legitimacy of the excessive VAT deductions applied,</seg>
<seg id="224">(d) the tax authorities have not sufficiently verified the imports and exports declared in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. Control findings in the SR</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Checking the selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">For a selected sample of SAO SR verified or carried out a tax audit for the tax year 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analysing the tax returns and refund requests submitted to the selected tax entities of the SAO SR, the tax office requested the provision of the relevant JCD proving imports and exports, invoices and proof of payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, the SAO SR checked whether the JCDs submitted were registered in the customs database of imports and exports and the fulfilment of the decisive facts and statutory conditions when applying the deduction of input tax on imports, on the refund of the excess VAT deduction, in the application of the exemption from export duty and when the SpD was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="230">The SAO SR verified at 10 audited tax offices selected cases of imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and the Czech Republic in the structure according to the honor of jcd items and the sum of statistical values shown in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="231">In total, imports were checked at a statistical value of EUR 856,2 million. Sk, which represents 5.11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic to the CFR.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were checked for a total statistical value of EUR 176 million. Sk, which represents 6.87% of the total value of exports of selected commodities from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="233">Furthermore, 618 cases of imports of other goods and services (mainly white equipment, packaging techniques and software) from EU countries to the SR were checked for a total statistical value of EUR 532.8 million. Group.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Synergies between tax and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="235">The SAO SR checked the tax offices to find discrepancies between the data recorded in the Customs Database of the Czech Republic and the data reported in specific VAT returns, e.g.:</seg>
<seg id="236">- 2 tax entities (natural persons) mentioned in the tax returns imports of goods with a total value of 1 589 261 Sk, on the basis of which they claimed the right to recover excessive VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="237">In local investigations carried out at the initiative of the SAO SR, tax entities have failed to demonstrate to the tax authority the legitimacy of the application of input tax by the relevant evidence of the execution of imports and payment of VAT,</seg>
<seg id="238">- the tax entity (s. r. o.) declared in the tax return for the tax year january 2003 the taxable transaction received in the value of 77 167 576 Sk, the export of goods worth 18 006 041 Sk and applied an excessive deduction of VAT of 17 157 101 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="239">It is apparent from the VAT returns filed for 2003 that the difference between the volume of purchases and exports of 59 161 535 Sk, which was established in January 2003, was not compensated during the whole of 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the above cases, the SAO SR asked the competent tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of the excessive VAT deductions applied.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, the tax entity (s. r. o.) for the tax year January to June 2002 indicated exports of goods with a total value of SK 87 199 in vat returns.</seg>
<seg id="242">Verification in the customs database of the Slovak Customs Database found that the tax entity carried out exports at a statistical value of 296 747 Sk during that period.</seg>
<seg id="243">The Tax Office carried out a local investigation at the company's headquarters, finding that the company's executive (UK citizen) had travelled and the company had left the leased premises without terminating the lease in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of the inspection of the SAO SR, the tax administrator notified the law enforcement authorities of the suspected non-tax charge of the offence.</seg>
<seg id="245">On the basis of the results of the audit at the selected tax offices, the SAO SR notes that the biggest problems in the administration and control of VAT and the SpD were mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- non-use of the possibility of carrying out vat checks on problematic tax entities, in particular in cases of the application of the high value of excessive VAT deductions,</seg>
<seg id="247">- the tax audit protocols did not contain an inventory of the documents checked</seg>
<seg id="248">- JCD on the import and export of goods,</seg>
<seg id="249">- insufficient screening of the reported import and export of goods in the tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="250">- lengthy proceedings by tax administrations in issuing decisions, in particular in the context of the assessment procedure, as well as the termination of the right to deduct sanctions,</seg>
<seg id="251">- non-compliance with the legal conditions in the provision of deferrals of payment of taxes,</seg>
<seg id="252">- non-compensation of VAT arrears within the time limit for the refund of the excess VAT deduction,</seg>
<seg id="253">- insufficient use of all forms of security and recovery of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">On the basis of the identified deficiencies identified, the SAO SR requested the competent tax authorities to carry out a VAT tax check, focusing on the legitimacy of the excessive VAT deductions applied for 14 tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="255">Measures have been taken at all audited tax offices to address the identified deficiencies, the fulfilment of which the SAO will monitor and control.</seg>
<seg id="256">6. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation made it possible to examine trade transactions between trading partners from both Countries and highlighted shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="258">The checks also resulted in the detection of persistent deficiencies in the fulfilment of the obligations of VAT and SpD payers, in the activities of financial and tax authorities, in the system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax and customs authorities, which ultimately reduced the efficiency and efficiency of tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="259">The findings also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have basic data on imports and exports from the Customs Database of the Czech Republic within the framework of the tax information system. There is no similar system in the Czech Customs and Customs Administration of information on imports and exports of goods.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the enforcement of VAT and SpD administration was not the same due to the different rules and conditions in the territory of the two States.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from the information obtained from the customs administration of the Czech Republic and from documents available at the audited tax offices. The SAO SR verified the execution of commercial transactions from documents of tax entities requested through tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="262">In the event of irregularities being detected, he asked the tax authorities to carry out tax checks.</seg>
<seg id="263">The parallel controls carried out in the field of VAT and the SpD assessed the state of the administration of these taxes in the period prior to accession to the European Union and pointed out the need for further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will be further intensified in the control of the activities of financial or tax authorities in connection with the adoption of the new VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations related to the supply of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of so-called 'goods'. recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="266">This report must be submitted by all VAT payers who have made the supply of goods to another Member State to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax authorities are obliged to enter recapitulative information data into the VAT Information Exchange System (VIES) to which tax authorities from the Member States of the European Union have access.</seg>
<seg id="268">The tax authorities and tax authorities can then compare these data with the data given in the VAT returns filed.</seg>
<seg id="269">This system is also used to verify the validity of the VAT registration number of persons registered for VAT, to verify the eligibility of the VAT exemption applied for the supply of goods to another Member State and to check the proper taxation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel control actions showed the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these control actions will be confronted with the outcomes of the forthcoming control actions, which will focus, inter alia, on the verification of the VIES system, which is intended to prevent tax evasion in the so-called "tax authorities". 'intra-Community supplies'.</seg>
<seg id="272">Given the importance of VAT and the SpD for budgetary revenues, control activities need to focus primarily on monitoring and identifying risk areas in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion in indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office and chairman of the Najvyššie Control Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
