<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of inspections in asylum facilities in the Czech Republic and slovakia</seg>
<seg id="2">State assets and funds intended to secure the activities of the Refugee Facility Administration of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="3">Control Action No 04/23 "State assets and funds intended to secure the activities of the Refugee Facility Administration of the Ministry of the Interior"</seg>
<seg id="4">Control Action No. 15/2004 "Control of the economy with the assets of the sting and financial prostrieds intended for the rationing of asylum and temporary shelter cudzincom in the SR"</seg>
<seg id="5">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">Population migration is one of the phenomena that are of a global character and have become an inseparable part of the current development stages of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">Its cause is, in particular, the escape of citizens from their country of origin or last residence from persecution, in particular on grounds of racial, religious, national, political, as well as the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Their aim is to gain asylum and integrate into society, especially in one of Europe's advanced democratic countries.</seg>
<seg id="9">A large group is also made up of foreigners, whose reason for migration is unfavourable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The adoption of the 1951 Geneva Agreement and the 1967 New York Protocol on the legal status of refugees, whose acceptance by the governments of the signatory countries had undertaken to apply them in their foreign policy orientation, has already been established.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federal Republics ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">After the split in 1993, both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue by continuing to comply with the adopted international documents and confirming their binding nature within the framework of national legislation by a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both republics have also enshrined asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">Parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší control office of the Slovak Republic, the results of which include a joint final report, were focused on the asylum process and related issues.</seg>
<seg id="16">Cooperation between the Supreme Audit Offices of the two countries was carried out on the basis of the 'Cooperation in Control Agreement' ('the Treaty') concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">In the Treaty, the two Parties undertook to provide each other with information on the legislation governing asylum procedures in the State of the other Contracting Party, selected statistics on the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as information on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the parallel control action was to type the same problem circuits and to highlight the consequences of this for population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted of the unification of the programme of control actions, the exchange of information to the extent laid down by the Treaty and the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">At the first joint meeting, which took place on 5-4 June 2005, the European Union adopted a report on the european union's role in the 2007-2014 until 7.4.2004, the same areas of controlled issues and control procedures in the preparation of control actions were established.</seg>
<seg id="21">At the second meeting, which took place on 28 and 28 June 2006, the European Union decided to take the to 30.6. 2004, the common points for the control action programme were specified.</seg>
<seg id="22">At the third joint meeting, which took place during the control action of 8.11. until 10.11.2004, the experience of ongoing checks was exchanged.</seg>
<seg id="23">The forms of outputs from the checks have been specified and the structure and content of the joint final report drawn up on 14.2 have been specified. to 17.2. 2005 at the last joint meeting.</seg>
<seg id="24">The checks were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by inspectors of the Department of Defence and Security and selected territorial departments.</seg>
<seg id="26">The persons audited were the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as the Ministry of the Interior) and the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "SUZ").</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic, it carried out a review of the sectiona of the defence, vnútra and štátnych úradov.</seg>
<seg id="28">The audited entity was the Migration Office of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Technical Party (hereinafter referred to as the "MÚ").</seg>
<seg id="29">The period audited was 2001, 2002, 2003 (hereinafter referred to as the audited period).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistical data over a longer period of time are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2. Recapitulation of the results of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. Evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of parallel checks was: - asylum process, - asylum facilities, - management of funds and state property, - internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of experience gained between the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyššší control office of the Slovak Republic took place at the stage of preparation and implementation of control actions.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange made it possible to evaluate the documents submitted more thoroughly, to analyse the causes of the identified differences in the security of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">Thus it was possible to focus on the decisive problems affecting the activities of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">In the end, this positively affected the quality of the inspection activity.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of the results of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonisation of the asylum law of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with European Union documents ('the EU') has been the subject of the European Commission's evaluation reports on the readiness of both countries to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">The adoption of legislation in this area continues after both countries have joined the EU with a view to further harmonisation with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants has a continuously increasing trend, with a significant increase in applicants in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic provide financial and material security to asylum seekers within the meaning of international agreements.</seg>
<seg id="44">The state budget of both countries allocates the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditure drawn from the state budget of both countries is mainly affected by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until the granting or non-granting of asylum, as well as the state of health of the applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">The amount of some of the benefits collected is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic set up asylum facilities in which they gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of the participants in the granting of asylum proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="48">In asylum facilities, accommodation, meals, health care and basic material equipment and hygiene supplies are provided to asylum seekers during their stay.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, courses are organized within the leisure activities and applicants are created conditions for cultural and sports activities.</seg>
<seg id="50">Asylum facilities include reception centres and residential centres, in the Czech Republic as well as integration centres.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cost of one stay day depends on the occupancy and amenities of the resort and is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is essentially stabilised.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is expected to increase by almost 1,000 places in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create conditions for applicants, the increasing number of which are expected to continue in the coming years in the context of the application of the Dublin Convention.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the highest part of the approved budget expenditure was spent on the security of services. The decisive expenditure of this item was the expenditure on accommodation and catering of applicants in asylum facilities operated under contract, the cost of healthcare provided to asylum seekers and the cost of a permanent security service ensuring the protection of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">Expenditure on salaries, payments for work carried out and insurance premiums also accounted for a significant extent in total expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of the migration policy and the asylum process has been marked by many budgetary measures that addressed legitimate requirements related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Expenditure on wages, salaries and insurance premiums, expenditure on materials and services and expenditure on security services were decisively involved in the utilisation of current expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the inspection in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic highlighted some similar shortcomings that did not have a major impact on the financial management and management of the state's assets.</seg>
