<p>
<seg id="1">Public procurement and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on parallel control carried out by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">The award of public contracts for goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and the private sector.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the State is to make the most efficient and economical use of public resources and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor for the success of the Single Economic Area.</seg>
<seg id="7">The EU has set limits in its rules, exceeding which the contracting authority must meet certain requirements to guarantee a broad and unhindered competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose european procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">Both the Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts that are valued below EU limits, the regulation of their award remains within the scope of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">Moreover, public procurement is prone to corruption, with a subsequent high potential for damage.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting entities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and unfair favoritism (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI – SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI – BRH) agreed to carry out parallel controls in the field of procurement procedures and to prevent corruption in land and transport buildings.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation was also focused on the area of European procurement law as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">The controls also included procurement below European limits in order to cover the area of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The control findings of the two SAIs are summarised in a joint report addressed, inter alia, to international organisations such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Areas of control and controlled institutions</seg>
<seg id="18">The BRH evaluation is based on area checks of the above mentioned areas, which were carried out by the German building authorities responsible for federal transport and construction between 2011 and 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, highway construction and large-scale construction projects were evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="20">The BRH included the findings of past controls in the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="21">The SAO's evaluation is based on inspections carried out during the years 2008 to 2012, which were focused on road constructions, railway lines, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other buildings in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, federal procurement is mostly carried out by the provincial building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, the state institution for road and rail construction is responsible for the award of public contracts in the field of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the field of civil engineering, public procurement is carried out by the beneficiaries of budgetary appropriations.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used at the various stages of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation takes into account the differences in public procurement legislation and the specificities of the construction market in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of the Public Procurement Act in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the course of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and statutory standards.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany shall be governed by budgetary law and the relevant administrative acts .</seg>
<seg id="30">Internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details on the requirements of european procurement law and the prevention of corruption are enshrined in the so-called 'european procurement law'. procurement manuals of the federal government, in which the requirements are elaborated or formulated in greater detail in the light of legal precedents in the field of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legislation concerning contracts with value above and below European limits.</seg>
<seg id="33">The procurement law undertouched substantial changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules have strengthened the transparency of procurement procedures, opened up space for more competition and reduced opportunities for corruption during the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="35">Fundamental aspects of the procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As regards European procurement procedures, open and narrower procedures must be applied in both countries in particular.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts under the European limit are awarded in accordance with national rules (public call for competition, limited call for participation, negotiated procedures), but these are practically identical to the above conditions for European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterised by the principle of the preference for open procedures (where candidates are invited on a European scale) and public calls for participation (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and when called to participate in a competition, any candidate may submit an offer.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is achieved mainly by dividing the total public contract into commercially specific parts and by dividing it into sub-contracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">The award of contracts divided into these parts gives the opportunity to participate in the proceedings to as many candidates as possible.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of the German procurement law are time-tested tools for obtaining good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are registered in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, the conditions of European procedures must also be applied in cases of public procurement with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">The exception is a simplified sub-limit procedure where the contracting authority can use less demanding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, the Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which the contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favourable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current Czech legislation allows contracting entities to choose between open procedures and narrower procedures.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are 85,000 construction companies registered in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">The total volume of contracting authority contracts for public works and the share of the different types of procedures in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction work in Germany amounted to EUR 7 675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">czk, of which CZK 1,138 billion was CZK (15%) the proportion of public contracts, which, in addition to contracts awarded by the federal government, included contracts awarded by individual Länder and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of projects of federal road and construction projects (excluding the construction of railways and water works) amounted to EUR 212.5 billion. Czk.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of federal contracts for land works and transport works was as follows: 80,7 % open management and public calls; 12.7% narrower management and narrower challenges;</seg>
<seg id="55">6,6 % of negotiated procedures and direct procurement; 33.2% is the share of European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic in 2011 amounted to EUR 118.6 billion. czk , which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction work.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, it amounted to EUR 194.0 billion. 37% of the total.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of procurement types in 2011: 65,1 % open procedures; 14.3 % narrower procedure; 9,5 % of the negotiated procedure; 8,4 % simplified procedures for sub-limit contracts; 2.7% other proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="59">Those figures shall include all public procurement contracts for supplies, services and works awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">The figures show that: parallel controls in both countries have focused on a substantial part of public procurement procedures; corruption prevention, which must still be taken into account in procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; open meaning. procurement procedures are of key importance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and BRH carried out parallel controls on the award of European works contracts, with an emphasis on preventing corruption in their countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The controls were aimed at comparing legislation in both countries and the EU and on the implementation of public procurement in the field of land and transport constructions.</seg>
<seg id="64">The following are key findings:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into the national rights of both countries (paragraphs 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">The prevention of corruption is not only the aim of the EU directive, but the national procurement rules of both countries, which differ in part in terms of focus and in detail.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the basic requirement that the tender documents must meet is to include all the information needed to prepare tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specifications shall be neutral and shall not contain any requirements limiting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tender documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, the problem is the lack of definition of the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, the division of contracts into parts is required where possible in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to brh findings, this requirement is being complied with in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">Sao's checks have shown that in the Czech Republic, very large public works in the field of road constructions are commissioned, without being divided into parts, or divided, but only in a very significant part of it. This method can distort competition and lead to restrictions on only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">Such constraints on market potential may result in a significant increase in costs and create a risk of non-serious pricing practices and inadmissible conventions.</seg>
<seg id="75">The legislation in both countries allows contracting entities to subsequently enter additional works under certain conditions if this need arises only after the conclusion of the contract (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">In both countries, the requirements for the correct identification of the type of procurement procedure are met.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, according to the applicable regulations, contracting entities can arbitrarily designate one of the open procurement procedures, namely an open procedure or a narrower procedure.</seg>
<seg id="78">German rules in the procurement and budgetary law give priority to open procedures for both European tenders and national, known as public calls for competition.</seg>
<seg id="79">Open procurement procedures in both countries allow a larger number of candidates to submit tenders and also reduce the risk of corruption by making it difficult to negotiate prices illegally between bidders.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best results are achieved in terms of value for money.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of large contracts whose estimated total price reaches or exceeds the limits set by the EU, the contracting entities audited have always awarded European tenders.</seg>
<seg id="82">The correct determination of the expected value of the contract plays a very important role in determining the type of procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used to objectively determine the price of public works, in which values are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is a sufficiently objective tool.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are used only in the area of road construction, but they are not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a works contract under European procurement procedures, it is necessary to publish preliminary information and notices of the opening of the procurement procedure in order to increase competition by allowing candidates to prepare in time for the submission of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction authorities audited complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, incorrect application of provisions and/or a lack of controls may have impaired competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">When selecting candidates to participate in a shortlisted procurement procedure, there is a greater risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be high enough to guarantee real competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria shall be objective, non-discriminatory and shall be published well in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition to EU requirements, contracting entities in both countries should take turns as often as possible to encourage candidates to participate in the procedure when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany, there are partly very detailed requirements for the prevention of manipulation risks.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the contracting entities audited did not comply with these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions have not always been credible (section 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting entities must ensure that all candidates wishing to submit a tender receive the same information during the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreement between those candidates and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of specifications shall be prevented as far as possible in order to avoid any reduction in competition in the form of unlawful agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the German contracting authorities audited did not comply with that requirement in several cases (point 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">The labelling, documentation, protection and confidentiality requirements of tenders are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">Checks in both countries found only a few cases of irregularities (section 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The assessment and evaluation of tenders is procedurally regulated in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more comprehensive, but have not always been respected by the contracting authorities under review.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting entities forwarded their tenders to third parties for inspection without prior consideration without properly documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">Thus, the tenders were insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulations (section 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">The intended award of the contract must be discussed by the participants for the sake of legal protection, enterprises are to be informed about the intended contract award before the latter is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection rule also is designed to prevent corruptive action.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of contract award procedures also for national tenders.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in few cases, the notification of the enterprises was not appropriately ensured (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The procurement documents were not always complete or entirely credible for the contracting authorities audited in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, the transparency requirements applied at European level have not always been properly respected in the management minutes.</seg>
