<seg id="620">In Germany, tenderers must remain silent and only the beneficiaries can participate in the evaluation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="621">Only the contracting authority may examine the mathematical accuracy of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="622">Only employees who are not included in the decision-making phase of the supplier's selection or the project implementation phase may be entrusted with the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="623">There are no precise provisions on who can carry out further reviews and evaluations.</seg>
<seg id="624">If external companies are entrusted with reviewing and evaluating tenders, they must be aware that the offers are confidential and respect this fact.</seg>
<seg id="625">They may only make proposals to the contracting authority for a decision.</seg>
<seg id="626">In the Czech Republic, tenders must be reviewed and evaluated by a commission appointed by the contracting authority, which draws up a report with a proposal for the conclusion of a contract.</seg>
<seg id="627">However, in both countries the final decision depends on the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="628">Where, in Germany, the documents and declarations required in connection with the submission of tenders are incomplete, the tenderers concerned must subsequently submit the required documents within six days.</seg>
<seg id="629">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="630">If tenderers fail to comply with this obligation, their tenders must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="631">In the Czech Republic, the contracting authority may decide whether to give the applicant the opportunity to supplement the missing documents.</seg>
<seg id="632">If the candidate does not prove them, they must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="633">In Germany, it is necessary to examine not only the total price, but also the unit prices.</seg>
<seg id="634">Where the price structure of the tender shows that the prices for parts of the overall project have been estimated disproportionately high or low, tenderers must be asked for an explanation.</seg>
<seg id="635">If they do not provide explanations and if the contracting authority can demonstrate that the tender contains compensatory prices, such tenders must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="636">This is intended to prevent tenderers from submitting price calculations on the assumption that substantial quantitative changes will be made to each part of the overall project, which can lead to a significant increase in project costs.</seg>
<seg id="637">In the Czech Republic, the total price of the work is evaluated and the prices of the individual parts are not examined in detail.</seg>
<seg id="638">Valuation compensation is not the reason for excluding the offer.</seg>
<seg id="639">In Germany, a contract cannot be awarded to a tenderer offering a disproportionately high or low price.</seg>
<seg id="640">Where one or more tenders differ in price by 10 % or more from the price estimated by the contracting authority or from other tenders, tenderers must demonstrate that their tender has been credibly and convincingly calculated.</seg>
<seg id="641">If they are unable to do so, the contracting authority should exclude them.</seg>
<seg id="642">In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure may be cancelled after a price review if only tenders with disproportionately low prices have been received and the tenderers have not justified those prices.</seg>
<seg id="643">If the price of the tender is substantially higher than the contracting authority's estimate, this is not the reason for refusing to award the contract to the tenderer concerned (unlike the German procurement law).</seg>
<seg id="644">Where there is a suspicion in Germany of conduct intended to restrict competition, the contracting authority shall immediately report this fact to the competent superior authority.</seg>
<seg id="645">It must decide on the next procedure and whether it is appropriate to inform the antitrust office or law enforcement authorities.</seg>
<seg id="646">It must also approve (e.g. when the contract exceeds €50,000 and the contract has not been awarded to the tenderer with the lowest bid), whether the contract will be awarded when the contract is discussed or whether the procurement procedure will be cancelled.</seg>
<seg id="647">Czech rules do not regulate this area.</seg>
<seg id="648">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="649">BRH</seg>
<seg id="650">Fitness check and procurement criteria</seg>
<seg id="651">Most of the procurement procedures examined were in line with the relevant requirements.</seg>
<seg id="652">In the case of certain recommendations of potential suppliers made by self-employed persons, the contracting authorities themselves did not check the suitability of tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="653">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="654">In some cases, there was insufficient documentation as to whether the contracting authority had taken into account all published evaluation criteria or whether the selection decision was based solely on the price criterion.</seg>
<seg id="655">Selection of interested parties and confidentiality of tenders</seg>
<seg id="656">Some contracting authorities used the services of unauthorized persons, such as self-employed persons or building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="657">They were incorporated into the planning or implementation process of construction projects, performing functions which were to be held exclusively by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="658">The contracting authorities have tried to justify this fact by their lack of human resources in the sector.</seg>
<seg id="659">In some cases, they used self-employed professionals to review the service offers of persons who were not formally bound to maintain the confidentiality of tenders and to carry out with due care the fulfilment of their obligations under the contract.</seg>
<seg id="660">As regards contracting entities, as a rule, there was no evidence as to whether the offers in the custody of self-employed professionals were only available to designated persons.</seg>
<seg id="661">Review and mathematical check of offers</seg>
<seg id="662">Some contracting entities have submitted open envelopes for further examination to self-employed experts without first carrying out the prescribed examination of tenders and a mathematical examination and without documenting the results of those examinations.</seg>
<seg id="663">In the event of any intention of manipulation, third parties may have made changes to tenders which could not be identified by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="664">The examination of the documents revealed a number of cases where unusual elements in the tenders were not adequately identified or where price and product data were missing.</seg>
<seg id="665">Performance audits</seg>
<seg id="666">A model inspection by one contracting authority revealed that in 75 % of the procurement procedures, the most advantageous tenders deviated by more than 10 % from the pre-estimated costs.</seg>
<seg id="667">One of the 20 procurement procedures was cancelled due to inadequate tender prices.</seg>
<seg id="668">In many cases, there was no evidence or sufficient documentation on the examination of tenders or negotiations with tenderers for further clarification.</seg>
<seg id="669">In many cases, detailed information was also also missing e.g. the unit prices of the most important invoiced items.</seg>
<seg id="670">Changes in market prices or an increase in material costs were often cited as the reason for the deviations.</seg>
<seg id="671">The contracting authorities argued that identifying and proving compensatory prices was difficult.</seg>
<seg id="672">In the case of one call for tenders made by an entity outside the ordinary contracting authorities, a 66 % lower price was offered compared to the original cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="673">Data on closer examination of the cost or on the determination of the reasons for the deviations were not recorded.</seg>
<seg id="674">In clarifying this question, the contracting authority found no indication of price dumping on the tenderer to whom the contract would eventually be awarded.</seg>
<seg id="675">It was therefore not clarified whether the initial cost estimate was excessive or whether the price offered was too low.</seg>
<seg id="676">Later, the contracting authority rated this tenderer as a 'low-cost company' which was unable to meet either the quality requirements or the deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="677">In another procurement procedure, the contracting authority awarded the contract to a tenderer whose price was 35 % higher than the original cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="678">The contracting authority did not cancel the procurement procedure and put forward an unfounded argument that the tenderer could be presumed not to base its pricing on a disproportionately high cost.</seg>
<seg id="679">Suspected irregularities</seg>
<seg id="680">One contracting authority found two cases of irregularities, and these were reported to the company responsible for technical supervision.</seg>
<seg id="681">In one procurement procedure, two tenderers submitted tenders containing an identical price calculation, which led the contracting authority to exclude both tenders.</seg>
<seg id="682">The checks did not show any substantial deficiencies in the application of the other provisions.</seg>
<seg id="683">Sao</seg>
<seg id="684">Verification of suitability</seg>
<seg id="685">For many construction projects, such as the construction of a building site, the university buildings, roads and railways, contracting entities have not excluded tenderers from participating in the procurement procedure, even if they have not complied with the requirements of the contracting authority referred to in the specifications, or have failed to provide the qualifications to the required extent, or, on the contrary, one contracting authority has failed to substantiate or explain the reason for the decommissioning of the candidate who complied with the requirements.</seg>
<seg id="686">Guest</seg>
<seg id="687">In the case of the construction of a waste water treatment plant, the individual evaluation criteria of the procurement procedure for the contractor were established, but the contracting authority did not respect them during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="688">For actions in the field of railway infrastructure development, the weighting of the award criteria at the start of the management was not determined at the start of the evaluation criteria, but only at the beginning of the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="689">For the road repair project, the evaluation of the criterion of 'reduction of construction time' was not correct.</seg>
<seg id="690">For second and third place bidders, the evaluation incorrectly indicated a greater reduction in construction time than indicated in their tenders.</seg>
<seg id="691">Documentation of the reasons for the selection of the candidate</seg>
<seg id="692">For the three housing promotion actions, the contracting authority has not demonstrated on the basis of which criteria it has assessed the tenders received and how it has selected the most suitable of them.</seg>
<seg id="693">The correctness of the selection of small-scale procurement suppliers associated with the construction of a road circuit with an estimated price of up to CZK 500,000 is correct.</seg>
<seg id="694">Czk could not be verified because the suppliers were selected only on the basis of telephone consultations on the price and date of performance, but documents on these negotiations were not produced.</seg>
<seg id="695">Summary</seg>
<seg id="696">In both countries, the rules for verifying and evaluating offers correspond to EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, they differ in view of the specific management steps and the selection of individuals involved in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="698">Unlike in the Czech Republic, these procurement process steps in Germany are governed by stricter and more detailed requirements, especially as regards the application of the cross principle and the protection of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the rules for verifying the appropriateness of the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, in some cases, controls found that the substantial steps of the process in verifying and evaluating tenders were not documented at all and, if so, only partially.</seg>
<seg id="701">The absence of control tools and transparency in decision-making during the review and evaluation of tenders makes it possible to manipulate.</seg>
<seg id="702">The checks have shown serious defects, such as the transmission of tenders to third parties without prior appropriate examination and documentation of tenders by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="703">Where contracting entities entrust a third party with the performance of functions related to the screening and evaluation of tenders, appropriate measures and increased control of measures against increased possibility of manipulation shall be necessary.</seg>
<seg id="704">In checking the eligibility of prices, the German contracting authorities audited did not use a complete set of available instruments in all cases and did not deal with their own price structure.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, weaknesses were found in the evaluation of the suitability of tenders and the use of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Completion of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="707">After review and evaluation of tenders, the procurement process shall be completed by the award of the contract or by the cancellation of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">Requirements of European law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In the case of a European procedure, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the award decision.</seg>
<seg id="710">Suppliers shall have the opportunity to review the decision taken within a limited period of 10 or 15 days and to request its review, if appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="711">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="712">The 10-day period applies to electronic submissions and 15 days to other submissions.</seg>
<seg id="713">The contract shall not be concluded before the expiry of that period or before the decision of the review procedure.</seg>
<seg id="714">If the review body rejects the complaint and confirms the decision, candidates and tenderers shall be given the opportunity to have the fairness of the application of the procurement law reviewed by an independent court.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting authority will be able to circumvent the legal protection of suppliers by the prompt implementation of the procurement procedure decision.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting authority shall properly document the progress of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries implemented management information obligations.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure rests with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, it cannot arbitrarily deviate from the results of a properly carried out examination and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority is to conclude the contract within the specified time.</seg>
<seg id="723">This is due to the fact that the tenderer is not bound by his tender after the expiry of that period.</seg>
<seg id="724">The content of the contract must not deviate from the winning offer.</seg>
<seg id="725">Unsuccessful tenderers should be informed of the result in a timely manner, stating the reason why their tender was not accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">The cancellation of a procurement procedure is permissible only if certain conditions are met, e.g. by the commission of a contract procedure. if the prices in the tenders do not conform to the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory waiting period before the conclusion of the contract of 10 or 15 days applies to European and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, the equivalent provision applies only to European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other proceedings in Germany, tenderers may not be informed of the award of the contract before deciding on its EU provisions and the award of a review.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure must be cancelled if a single tender has been received or only one tender has met the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, a contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that the tender meets the conditions laid down in the tender documents and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">Checks found few irregularities in the completion of the audited procurement processes.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases, European proceedings have received companies authorising letters before the notification period expires, which may invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also, in several open cases, the authorising letters of modification incompatible with the content of the tender, e.g. in the form of a tender, were included in the form of an open procedure. new deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, contracting entities have failed to meet the time limits for awarding the contract.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous tender because the tenderer offering a price of more than 50 % lower no longer wished to fulfil the contract at the originally offered price.</seg>
<seg id="740">Sao</seg>
<seg id="741">In one case, during the reconstruction and construction of the higher education institution, the contracting authority did not conclude a contract for the work with the contractor in accordance with the draft contract contained in the tender of the selected tenderer.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some road repair and maintenance events, the construction of a motorway and a road circuit, contracts were concluded later than required by law.</seg>
<seg id="743">For construction modifications in former military raids, the contracting authority sent a notice of selection of the most suitable tender to all tenderers only after the legal deadline had expired.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented EU rules on the termination of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="746">The legal protection of failed candidates contributes to reducing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Act also includes the Institute of Legal Protection in cases of contracts below EU limits.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, it was found that a limited time limit for the conclusion of the contract had been exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can cause adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, contracting entities should eliminate such deficiencies in the conclusion of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notification, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process, with all its individual stages, relevant findings and decisions, including relevant justifications, shall be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">The completion of the procurement procedure at European level must be published.</seg>
<seg id="754">The data on procurement procedures are summarised in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of European law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document procurement procedures is in line with the fundamental requirement of the principle of transparency applied at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only proper and time-relevant documentation on decision-making and justification guarantees transparency in the procurement process and, above all, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each tenderer in cases where the value of the contract exceeds European limits.</seg>
<seg id="758">Appropriate documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, since the obligation to justify individual decisions in detail and their merits significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In the case of European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must notify the EU's Office of Official Publications within 48 days of the date of award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Authority publishes the notification in the Official Journal of the EU and the requirement of transparency is also fulfilled.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarise the relevant information on its procurement procedures and communicate them to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission publishes annual statistics to gain an overview of the development of the single market in the field of construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries fully transposed the provisions of the European Law on Documentation and Notification Obligations into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for the purposes of European statistics are almost the same in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to notify the award of a contract does not only apply to European procedures, but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notification period is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those which are compulsory under European law, applies only to restricted procedures exceeding the 25,000 limit. € (625 ths. and direct proceedings exceeding the limit of CZK 15,000. € (375 ths. czk) incl. VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Only the parties are informed below this limit.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of assignments have not been fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, e.g. the reasons for supply specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of one procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it had concluded a contract with a tenderer whose tender did not contain mandatory requirements.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases, some required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Publication of the award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="780">In the case of certain European procedures, the contracting authority made no errors in the publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In the case of several assignments, there was no evidence of publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="782">Notification obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">Statistically tested files included the required minimum of information and were created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Preliminary transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority published information on the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting authority, the contract information was not disclosed due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the sponsor six months to notice the errors.</seg>
<seg id="788">Consequently, the outcome of the proceedings was not disclosed during that period.</seg>
<seg id="789">Sao</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">For events related to the organisation of a major sporting event, significant deficiencies were identified in the documentation on the conduct of the procurement procedure, such as the award procedure. incorrect information on bid prices in the protocols from the evaluation committee meetings.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some documents about opening envelopes have not been signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Publication of the award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="794">In the preparation of repairs and maintenance of roads, the construction of the motorway and the road circuit, the contract award notices were sent after the deadline or not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">The provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations include European requirements and are almost the same in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">Czech notification obligations are somewhat stricter compared to German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The checks revealed shortcomings substantially reducing the value of documentation as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to strengthen the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with the notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">Parallel controls of the SAO and BRH were focused on two areas which are relevant to the procurement process in both the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation gives an opportunity for international competition within the EU with a view to creating a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Measures aimed at preventing corruption are not only intended to avoid or at least reduce corruption, but also to prevent financial damage and possible losses of confidence in the integrity of the government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The findings of the two audit institutions – the SAO and the BRH – with regard to the application of the procurement law of the two countries and the comparison of its relevant provisions give an internal view of the common and distinct elements that can assist the two countries in further developing and applying that right.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries transposed EU public procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">In both countries, there is thus an important common basis for public procurement and fulfilment of the essential requirements in the field of: competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting entities reinforce these requirements in part by very large-scale measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has applied provisions on public procurement requiring European management as well as to procedures that are below EU limits and is therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the checks have shown that contracting entities do not always fully comply with all relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate the irregularities mentioned, taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, the controls identified risks affecting economy and achievement of value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">This concerns, in particular, the incomplete definition of the subject-matter of the contract, which has resulted in additional works which have often been commissioned in breach of the law, the lack of definition of the intended price and the required qualification assumptions narrowing the possible range of tenderers and thus reducing competition, in particular in the field of transport constructions.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">Joint controls were not intended to detect cases of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="818">This was because both BRH and the SAO do not have the tools to do so.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they can examine whether the competent authorities of both countries are taking measures to reduce corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">When it comes to preventing corruption, the two countries have focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">In particular, the German provisions give scope for widespread and unlimited competition, transparency and controls as a central element in the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">In particular, Czech regulations monitor the strengthening of the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, there are general principles for the prevention of corruption that apply to the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles have also been incorporated between public procurement requirements and have been adopted to meet the specific needs of such procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, sometimes very precisely, ways of complying with the requirements for the prevention of corruption during the procurement procedure and for the selection of persons included therein.</seg>
<seg id="827">In THE BRH's view, the principle of the preference for open procurement procedures and calls for participation is a particularly appropriate tool for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in public procurement, while reducing competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate control (in particular the principle of cross-checking), transparency requirements, procurement documents and various organisational measures are also an effective mechanism for preventing corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore does not feel the need for substantial changes to the current provisions that public institutions must comply with when awarding public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The irregularities found in some areas highlighted weaknesses in compliance with some requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting entities should provide their staff with further training, thus familiaring them with anti-corruption requirements and further raising their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant proportion of the weaknesses identified relate to activities delegated by the construction administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the absence of adequate controls in the delegation of powers increases the risk of abuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Activities prone to manipulation and corruption should therefore only be transferred to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorised interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">Sao</seg>
<seg id="837">Anti-corruption strategies have been adopted at government level in the Czech Republic, which also have a significant concern in the area of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="838">The SAO's control actions took place during the period when one of the most important parts of this strategy was implemented, namely a significant change in the Public Procurement Act and the adoption of follow-up implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The adopted strategy and the new legislation can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">For example, under the new rules, the contracting authority must justify the effectiveness of the contract, the determination of the projected value of the contract, the adequacy of the requirements for qualification assumptions, the establishment of the basic evaluation criteria and the method of evaluation of tenders and the proper substantiation and publication of everything.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, both the SAO and BRH have a favourable opinion on the ways in which EU requirements are implemented.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their broad application in practice has confirmed that EU requirements for competition, equal treatment and transparency form an appropriate basis for eu procurement.</seg>
<seg id="844">The transnational model introduced in the EU can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the great potential of material and intangible damages resulting from manipulation and corruption in connection with public procurement, both the BRH and the SAO insist that it is the obligation of the contracting authorities to continue measures against corruption and manipulation and to improve them where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organisational structures and procurement processes should be continuously monitored in terms of weaknesses and risks in order to identify and respond appropriately to corrective action.</seg>
<seg id="847">Compared to practice in Germany, it has been apparent that the share of open procurement procedures should be increased in the Czech Republic, which give space to competition and substantially reduce the possibility of corrupt behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="848">The award of contracts in parts may also have a positive impact on the price achieved in cases where this is permissible and appropriate for the contracting authorities. A higher number of applicants creates pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">The provision of his organisation also affects the conduct of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany it is provided by special state organizations, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport constructions, it is organised by the central authorities themselves or through contractual organisations.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both the SAO and the BRH wish to further develop the knowledge in their work where appropriate and to address them with their parliament and government beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Moreover, they are convinced that the principles of the procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), as these principles and findings are of general importance for the effective fight against corruption and for the guarantee that public contracts are awarded under a well-functioning and honest competition regime and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="853">Annex</seg>
</p>
