<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in the controls of excise duty management between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The present joint report shall inform about the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší control office of the Slovak Republic, focused on the management of excise duties in the period after the entry of the two countries into the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement in control activities concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel controls was selected in view of the fundamental change in the system of collection of excise duties, which took place in connection with the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union from 1 January 2004. They shall forthed 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the European Union's internal market requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow the circulation of uninterdened goods until the date of delivery for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with that principle, the new legislation adopted in both countries allows the movement of goods under tax supervision under the conditional exemption regime.</seg>
