<seg id="150">5. International exchange of information between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="151">The conditions for cooperation between the administrative authorities of the Member States responsible for the management of excise duties were governed by 30 June 2005. It is necessary to provide for the assistance of the member states' competent authorities in the field of direct taxation, certain excise duties and insurance premium taxes.</seg>
<seg id="152">On 1 January 2005, the Council adopted Decision Regulation No 2073/2004 lays down rules and procedures allowing the competent authorities of the Member States of the European Union to cooperate and exchange the information necessary for the correct assessment of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="153">Each Member State shall designate a central liaison office which shall ensure contacts with other Member States in the field of excise management and shall be responsible for the exchange of information on the movement of excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="154">In the Czech Republic, the report "Excise Liaison Office" (hereinafter referred to as "ELO ČR") was set up at DGC to ensure the exchange of information in the field of excise duties between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="155">The security of tasks related to the management of systems for the control of the movement of excise goods (SEED, MVS, EWSE) and the exchange of information in the framework of mutual administrative assistance between the Member States of the European Union and the SR shall be carried out with effect from 1 January 2007. The office of ELO at the Customs Office of Poprad was asked to do so by 15 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="156">With effect from 1 January 2005, the On 1 July 2005, the tasks of elo are carried out by the ELO Department (with its registered office in Poprad) of the Department of Excise Duties of the Customs Directorate of the Czech Customs (ELO SR).</seg>
<seg id="157">In accordance with the provisions of Article 3(1) of Regulation (EC) No 126 In particular, the central liaison office is responsible for the exchange of data contained in the electronic REGISTER of SEED, - the Early Warning System Excise ('EWSE'), - requests for verification of the movement of excise goods sent to or received from other Member States by the 'Early Warning System Excise' ('MVS').</seg>
<seg id="158">The content, scope and functionality of SEED, EWSE and MVS are regulated in Articles 22, 23 and 24 of Regulation No 2073/2004.</seg>
<seg id="159">SEED - a system for the exchange of information on tax entities trading in excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="160">The system consists of national registers of excise payers and enables tax authorities in the Territory of the European Union to ascertain whether products subject to excise duty are traded by a person entitled to do so.</seg>
<seg id="161">Each national register shall be made available to the competent authorities of the other Member States only for the purposes of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="162">The central liaison office of each Member State shall ensure that persons involved in the movement of excise goods within the territory of the European Union can obtain confirmation of the information stored in that database.</seg>
<seg id="163">In accordance with Section 41 of Act No. 98/2004 Z. z., with Section 39 of Act No. 104/2004 Z. z., with Section 46 of Act No. 105/2004 Z. z., s § 40 of Act No. 106/2004 Z. z. z. and with § 39 of Act No. 107/2004 Z. z. z. ELO SR maintains an electronic database containing a register of operators of tax warehouses, authorized recipients and tax warehouses - database SEED.</seg>
<seg id="164">The customs authorities in the SR contribute to the SEED database by registering the tax warehouse, the tax warehouse operator or the authorized consignee in the SysNed application software, which is automatically linked to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="165">For example, if a new tax warehouse operator, authorized recipient, or tax warehouse is registered in the SysNed database, the related data is automatically transferred to the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="166">The SAO SR found that the exchange of SEED databases between the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic and the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic took place in the audited period, usually once a month, exceptionally multiple times a month.</seg>
<seg id="167">The SR Customs received 22 SEED files and sent 25 SEED files.</seg>
<seg id="168">Data to the SEED database in the Czech Republic are transferred from the national register, in which all persons authorised to dispose of products subject to excise duty and issued authorisations for handling these products are registered.</seg>
<seg id="169">Individual customs offices in the Czech Republic do not have access to the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="170">Requests from customs authorities to provide information from the SEED database of other Member States are obtained only through ELO ČR.</seg>
<seg id="171">EWSE - an early warning system aimed at controlling the transport of excise goods through which the transport of risky consignments is announced.</seg>
<seg id="172">The transport of certain products subject to excise duty in quantities exceeding the limits laid down by the European Commission regulation and, on the other hand, transport which is assessed as a risk by the tax authorities is considered to be a risky consignment.</seg>
<seg id="173">The exchange of information is carried out in two forms:</seg>
<seg id="174">- information - sent when the limits are exceeded,</seg>
<seg id="175">- warning message - sent if the transport of goods is assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="176">When assessing the risk level of a consignment, ELO SR uses the SEED database to send the warning message, on the basis of which it checks the data contained in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the event that the SEED database does not match the data in the accompanying document (for example, the registration number of the consignee or the registered office of the consignee does not match), ELO SR draws up a warning message to be sent to the ELO office of the Member State of the recipient of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="178">The ELO shall, when drawing up the reports, be governed by the regulations of the Tax and Customs Commission CED 317 and CED 457, which determine, inter alia, the type and quantity of goods in the relevant units of measure for the preparation of information and warning reports.</seg>
<seg id="179">In the audited period ELO SR sent ELO CR one warning message.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, information about started deliveries of products in quantities exceeding the specified limits is generated automatically when entering data from the accompanying document into the database when approving transport.</seg>
<seg id="181">If the tax administrator in the Czech Republic evaluates the consignment as a risk on the basis of its own analysis, it will process the so-called a warning message sent by ELO CR to the member state concerned.</seg>
<seg id="182">In 2005 ELO ČR sent two warning messages to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="183">MVS - the system of control of the movement of goods - allows, through requests from the MVS, to control the individual transport of products subject to excise duty as well as to check the specified route of transport between the operators indicated in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="184">The exchange of information shall take place on the basis of a request in which the ELO of the sending country specifies its requirements.</seg>
<seg id="185">The system shall be used in particular in cases where the consignor takes over the certified copy No 3 of the accompanying document and requires, for example, the use of a copy of the accompanying document. refund of excise duty and in cases where the particulars on the accompanying document cannot be verified in the international SEED database.</seg>
