<p>
<seg id="1">Value added tax administration in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of the follow-up</seg>
<seg id="3">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxation is generally a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">It goes without saying that the Supreme Audit Institutions (SAI) should focus their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">Examples include value added tax fraud (hereinafter also 'VAT').</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, a loss of EUR 100 billion is estimated annually in the European Union (hereinafter referred to as the "EU").</seg>
<seg id="8">As early as 2005, participants in the VI had become more interested in the use of the the euroai congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">As part of this cooperation, SAIs can exchange control procedures, find the best solution, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very suitable area for control cooperation, as it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrenungshof, hereinafter referred to as "BRH") carried out the first parallel control action in the field of VAT in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The relevant report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is not limited to a single country, but is widespread throughout the EU, close cooperation between the SAIs is needed to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the steps taken to tackle this problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two SAIs therefore decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out a subsequent parallel check.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Check number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of inspection: (CZ) Value added tax administration (D) Bilateral audit with THE SAO (follow-up)</seg>
<seg id="18">Objective of the inspection:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the control action was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the management of VAT, in particular to verify the procedure for dealing with selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as "Germany"), and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of both countries in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The control action was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">The intention was also to cover other VAT-related areas.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control findings were intended to be compared with the proven best practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The period audited was the years 2006 to 2008, in the case of material contexts, the period preceding and following, until the completion of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">The follow-up control of VAT management in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">Suspicious cases of intra-Community transactions were detected during previous parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them required further vetting.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the control findings, the two SAIs made recommendations on VAT management.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up control action carried out was used to evaluate the measures taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspicious cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The check was further targeted, e.g. by the commission. selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in debt collection and the implementation of VAT controls on large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">When checking vat management in selected areas in both countries, the inspectors reached the following control findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations from the previous inspection</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: The conditions for registering payers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel checks, comparisons of VAT registration systems in both countries found differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">As different forms of registration cause problems, the two SAIs recommended harmonising the conditions for registration of payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation has been presented at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The proposal for an amendment to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218/92 (hereinafter referred to as "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003") called for the extension of existing databases within the EU, including a database of VAT payers' vat identification numbers.</seg>
<seg id="38">It also amended common standards for the registration and deregistration of tax payers.</seg>
<seg id="39">THE SAI expected EU Member States to agree on appropriate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of that document, agreed by the EU Member States under ECOFIN, no longer contains the issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to regard this intention as a relevant tool for prevention in the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly reporting of summary reports</seg>
<seg id="44">In the framework of international cooperation, the previous control action recommended that all EU countries introduce a monthly deadline for reporting, allowing for a more timely examination of intra-community transaction values.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax to combat intra-Community tax evasion reduces the period for which summary reports on intra-EU transactions are reported to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1 January 2007. It was implemented from 1 January 2010, and was implemented in Germany from 1 January 2010. They are very, on 17 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to submit monthly summaries was not introduced within the deadline in accordance with the applicable EU rules, whereas in the Czech Republic it did.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Comparison of vat declaration data and summary reports in Germany in order to achieve greater reliability of data in VIES and consideration of the interconnection of the two VAT return systems and for summary reports</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted the BRH's recommendations and set up a working group to explore possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">Work is still ongoing and BRH will closely monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Sharing of successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system at EU level Based on the results of the previous control action, the two SAIs agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by only one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system need to be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, the perpetrators of fraudulent activity will choose the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The inspection found that our two Member States use different risk management systems that have their advantages and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the SAO has carried out a eurocanet review, which allows for the exchange of information within the EU, while brh has focused on German participation in the so-called 'eurocalnet'. risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Follow-up of selected intra-Community transactions cases</seg>
<seg id="57">During the previous control action, commercial transactions were jointly examined for which there were doubts about their implementation or irregularities in the reporting of commercial transactions in tax returns or summary reports to tax payers from both countries.</seg>
